Phase 3 Reflection

Phase 3 of the Cyber Risk Portfolio focused on building a simulated AWS cloud environment and performing a risk assessment based on real system configurations. The purpose of this phase was to connect technical infrastructure with business-focused cybersecurity analysis. By deploying a working environment that included a public web server, internal database server, and cloud storage, this phase demonstrated how vulnerabilities in a system directly impact business assets such as customer data, system availability, and organizational trust.

One of the most important aspects of this phase was the ability to identify and analyze vulnerabilities within a real environment. Unlike theoretical exercises, the AWS lab provided hands-on experience with common cloud misconfigurations such as publicly accessible storage, open SSH access, and exposed services. These findings were then evaluated based on their business impact, reinforcing the importance of aligning cybersecurity decisions with organizational priorities rather than focusing only on technical severity.

The most difficult task in this phase was configuring and troubleshooting the AWS infrastructure. Setting up the VPC, subnets, routing, and EC2 instances required careful attention to detail, as even small misconfigurations could prevent the system from functioning correctly. Additionally, understanding how different components interact, such as security groups and routing tables, added complexity to the process. However, overcoming these challenges provided a deeper understanding of cloud architecture and security design.

The most critical task for future phases was the vulnerability identification and risk analysis. This step builds the foundation for all future decision-making, including mitigation strategies and overall system improvement. By clearly linking vulnerabilities to business impact, the project moves beyond a simple technical assessment and becomes a comprehensive cyber risk evaluation. This approach reflects real-world cybersecurity practices and highlights the importance of integrating technical knowledge with business analysis.
